===Etymology===
{{ja-kanjitab|たから|yomi=k}}
From {{inherited|ja|ojp|-|sort=たから}}, ultimately from {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|*takara|sort=たから}}, being a compound of {{cog|ojp|-|sort=たから}} elements {{com|ja|sort=たから|高|tr1=taka|t1=high, expensive|等|tr2=-ra|t2=pluralizer}}, from the idea of treasure being a very valuable collection of items. The pluralizing suffix ''-ra'' is found in words such as {{m|ja|桜|tr=sakura|t=cherry blossom, cherry tree}}, {{m|ja|枕|tr=makura|t=pillow}}, {{m|ja|蹈鞴|tr=tatara|t=foot bellows}}, and other {{w|Japanese language|Japanese}} pronouns indicating direction or an area, such as {{m|ja|いくら|tr=ikura|t=how much}}, {{m|ja|どちら|tr=dochira|t=which way}}, and {{m|ja|こちら|tr=kochira|t=this way}}.<ref>{{R:ja:Martin 1987}}</ref>

First cited to the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'', compiled 759 {{CE}}.<ref>{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2|宝・財・貨}}</ref>

Alternatively, derived from a compound of {{com|ja|田|tr1=ta|t1=paddy field|から|tr2=kara|t2=from|lit=from the paddy fields}}, from the way people value thriving paddy fields as irreplaceable treasure.<ref>[https://www.takarashuzo.co.jp/takarahatakara/ 宝は田から～私たちの原点～ | 宝酒造株式会社] - Treasure is from the rice fields -Our Beginning- | Takara Shuzo (In Japanese)</ref>

